#: ../../source/user_guide/meshes.rst:317 fed770f2fdc34cd8adfe752168ad8e92
msgid ""
"The ``reorder=True`` flag is **required when ingesting Gmsh or VTK** "
"data: those formats use a different node-ordering convention for quads, "
"hexes, and high-order elements than TensorMesh's internal lexicographic "
"layout. Skipping it produces silently-broken basis-function evaluations. "
"The built-in generators already handle this, so you only need "
"``reorder=True`` on external files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/meshes.rst:324 2ca7f29e378846d695aac7b4aefeed54
msgid ""
"For a side-by-side visual of the two conventions — TensorMesh's internal "
"numbering on top, Gmsh / VTK on the bottom, for triangles, quads, tets, "
"and hexes at orders 2–4 — see :ref:`node-ordering-gallery`. That gallery "
"is the easiest way to verify which convention a hand-rolled connectivity "
"array is using."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/meshes.rst:330 a4891142d51b48a898e948e5a2e58606
msgid "**Saving.** Whatever format meshio writes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/user_guide/meshes.rst:337 ee1ba5cea64c465c85fce7c94bfd891a
msgid ""
"For ``.vtk`` and ``.vtu`` outputs, ``save`` automatically reorders back "
"to VTK convention and pads 2D coordinates to 3D — no flag needed. The "
"lower-level :meth:`~tensormesh.Mesh.to_meshio` returns the meshio object "
"directly if you need custom write logic."
msgstr ""

